Dennis A. Nowak, Joachim Hermsdörfer,
and Helge Topka
Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis is a degenerative motor neuron disorder with
progressive and exclusive loss of motor neurons in the spinal cord, brainstem,
and motor cortex. Five patients with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, and 5 age-
matched, healthy control subjects performed vertical point-to-point arm move-
ments with an instrumented hand-held object. In between the movements, the
object was held stationary. Compared with healthy controls, all patients gen-
erated greater grip forces during the phase of stationary holding of the object
and greater ratios between grip and load force maximums during the arm
movements. We conclude that in amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, the ability to
scale the grip force magnitude efficiently according to the actual loading re-
quirements is impaired. When performing upward movements, controls in-
creased grip force in parallel with load force right from the movement onset;
during downward movements, controls anticipated an early decrease of load
force by constant or decreasing grip forces. In contrast, 3 of 5 patients showed
an early increase of grip force during both upward and downward movements,
indicating that in amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, the differential regulation of
the grip force output according to the direction-dependent load force profile
may be impaired. In motor neuron disease, the inaccurate grip force scaling
and the impaired temporal coupling between grip and load force profiles may
either directly result from deficient motor execution or be secondary to ac-
companying symptoms, such as dyscoordination of hand and finger muscles
due to spasticity.

of environmental demands. The coordination between grip and load forces when
grasping, lifting and holding objects has been described in detail by Johansson,
Westling and their co-workers (Johansson, 1996; Johansson & Westling, 1984,
1988). These researchers have demonstrated that lifting and holding of objects is
achieved by a complex interplay between forward mechanisms that adjust grip
forces in anticipation of external object properties and feedback mechanisms that
modify finger forces when a change in object loading has been encountered

When a hand-held object is vertically moved in a point-to-point fashion, it is
first accelerated from rest and then decelerated to be held stationary again at the
desired end position. In this situation, grip force has to overcome acceleration-
induced inertial loads of the grasped object. During vertical point-to-point move-
ments with a hand-held object, load force fluctuates, reaching a maximum early in
upward and late in downward movements. In healthy adults, grip force increases
in parallel with load force during the acceleratory phase of an upward movement
and during the deceleratory phase of downward movement (Flanagan & Wing,
1993; Wing, 1996). A grip force maximum coincides with maximum load force
early in upward and late in downward movements. When the object is held in the
air at rest in between single movements, only its weight has to be counteracted by
adequate grip forces. The close temporal coupling between grip and load forces
during vertical point-to-point movements indicates acquired knowledge about the
environmental effects of arm movements on a hand-held load. An internal model
of feedforward grip force regulation based on an internal sensorimotor representa-
tion of both the limb dynamics and the physical object properties has been sug-
gested (Blakemore et al., 1998; Flanagan & Wing, 1997).
Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a progressive degenerative disorder
of motor neurons in the spinal cord, brainstem, and motor cortex (Lawyer & Netsky,
1953; World Federation of Neurology, 1994). The disease manifests clinically with
progressive muscular weakness, atrophy, and corticospinal tract signs in various
combinations. In its most typical form, awkwardness in tasks requiring fine finger
movements (e.g., difficulties with buttons), stiffness of the fingers, and weakness
or wasting of the hand muscles are first indications of the disease. In its later stages,
the disease presents the characteristic triad of atrophic weakness of the hands and
forearms, spasticity of the arms and legs, and generalized hyperreflexia, all in the
absence of sensory deficits. Abductors, adductors, and extensors of fingers and
thumb tend to become weak before the long flexors, on which the hand grip de-
pends, and the dorsal interosseous spaces become hollowed.

have been reported. In particular, deficits of efficient grip force scaling and re-
duced temporal precision of the grip and load force coupling were observed in

function. Recently, we investigated the coordination between grip and load forces
in a single case of ALS (Nowak & Hermsdörfer, 2003). This patient established
inefficiently elevated grip forces against the hand-held object, and the temporal
regulation of the grip force profile was similar for upward and downward move-
ments. Thus, the grip force profile was not adequately processed to match the
differential loading requirements of upward and downward movements. Given the
variability of clinical symptoms resulting in a wide span of disability, we extend
our previous study to investigate grip force regulation in ALS patients during per-
formance of vertical point-to-point arm movements with a hand-held instrumented
test object.
ALS is an unique model with solitary impairment of descending motor path-
ways without additional lesions of peripheral or central afferent systems. We hy-
pothesize that deficient grip force adjustments during vertical point-to-point arm
movements with a hand-held object in ALS primarily result from less effective and
uncoordinated force execution, rather than from impaired afferent sensory pro-
cessing. As demonstrated in our previous study, deficits in the control of grip force
may affect the temporal coordination between grip and load force profiles and/or
the efficient scaling of the grip force magnitude according to the actual loading
requirements.
Five patients (3 female, 2 male) with ALS participated in the present study. The
mean age of patients was 73.8 years. The duration of symptoms varied between 1
and 3 years (mean, 1.6 years). Clinical details of the ALS patients are summarized
in Table 1. Patients were diagnosed during hospitalization at the Department of
Neurology and Clinical Neurophysiology, Academic Hospital München-
Bogenhausen. The performance of patient E.E. had been described before in a
single case-control observation. Usually, patients presented with a history of one
or more of the following symptoms: progressive dysarthrophonia, dysphagia, weak-
ness of arm, hand and leg muscles. Neurological examination usually revealed
dysarthrophonia; dysphagia; generalized muscle fasciculations; weakness of arm,
shoulder, leg, and hip muscles; weakness and wasting of the small hand muscles.
There was commonly mild to moderate spasticity in all muscle groups of the upper
and lower extremities, tendon reflexes were brisk on both upper and lower ex-
tremities, and the Babinski signs were positive on one or both sides. There were
generally no sensory deficits. Patients were able to perform all motor activities of
daily life but noticed early fatigue during prolonged manual activities and when
walking longer distances. The electromyography was consistent with a general-
ized lesion of the spinal motor neurons, and affection of the cortical motor neurons
was demonstrated by delays of the central motor conduction times as demonstrated
by corbical magnetic stimulation to both upper and lower extremities. Further clini-
cal and apparative investigations excluded cervical myelopathy, paraneoplastic syn-
drome, cerebral and spinal cord lesions, such as syringomyelia, motor neuropathy,
chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy, and neuronal ganglioside
GM 1 antibodies in all patients. Patients’ family and previous medical history was
unremarkable. In particular, there was no history of spinal trauma or irradiation.

The motor function of the patients was assessed by the Amyotrophic Lateral Scle-
rosis Severity Scale (ALSSS; Hillel et al., 1989).
Five age- and sex-matched healthy subjects served as controls (mean age,
73.6 years). All participants used their dominant right hand to perform the experi-
ments. The patients were tested without medication and had no difficulties in per-
forming the entire set of motor tasks. Informed consent was obtained from all
participants. The study was conducted in accordance with the Declaration of
Helsinki and was approved by the local ethics committee.
Participants grasped a cylindrical and cordless instrumented object between the
tips of the thumb and other fingers on either side. The manipulandum and the
configuration of the hand and fingers used to grasp it are illustrated in Figure 1A.
The mass of the object was 0.350 kg. The object had a diameter of 9.0 cm and a
depth of 4.0 cm. Grip surfaces were of polished aluminum in all trials performed.
The object incorporated a force sensor for grip force registration and linear accel-
eration sensors for registration of kinematic acceleration signals in three dimen-
sions (see Figure 1A; Nowak et al. 2001, 2002, 2003; Nowak & Hermsdörfer,
2003). The force sensor registered grip forces at two different sensitivities be-
tween 0–10 N (0.0025 N/bit) and 0–50 N (0.0125 N/bit). The linear acceleration
sensors measured linear acceleration within a range of

Thus, when we manipulate objects, we rely more on a forward force control policy

than on feedback information from the grasping digits, which impose time lags
due to central loop processing. However, feedback signals from mechanoreceptors

The motor cortex plays a crucial role in the regulation of grip force during
object manipulation. The primary motor cortex directly influences distal arm, hand,
and finger muscles engaged in grasping through its direct connections with motor-
neurons in the spinal cord (Buys et al., 1986; Hepp-Reymond & Wiesendanger,
1972; Lemon et al., 1986). The hand area of the motor cortex receives propriocep-
tive and cutaneous afferent input from the arm and hand (Strick & Preston, 1982),
and interruption of the spinal dorsal columns or disconnection between the first
somatosensory and motor cortices result in deficits of the fine motor control of the
hand (Asanuma & Arissian, 1984) similar to those observed in pyramidal tract
lesions (Hepp-Reymond & Wiesendanger, 1972). It has been demonstrated that
proprioceptive and cutaneous afferent information significantly modulates motor
cortical activity and that physical object properties, such as weight and surface
friction, are well represented in the discharge of cortical motor neurons (Picard &
Smith, 1992). ALS is a degenerative disorder that affects solitarily the cortical and
spinal motor neurons without additional sensory dysfunction, and it seems fruitful
to study grip force regulation in a condition of exclusive dysfunction of the execu-
tive system of descending motor commands.

information obtained  from manipulation of hand-held objects to effectively select

previous object manipulations play a crucial role in the prediction of the conse-

finding that patients with ALS employed greater grip forces and consequently a

descending motor commands for the regulation of the grip force magnitude were
processed with impaired force economy. The predictive grip force scaling seems

mentary motor, premotor, and cingulate motor cortices) and the cerebellum coop-
erate when controlling human hand and finger movements. Studies on humans
performing manual tasks using positron emission tomography and functional mag-
netic resonance imaging demonstrated that several motor cortices are organized in
distributed and parallel patterns through basal ganglia-thalamo-cortical and
cerebello-thalamo-cortical projections (Hoover & Strick, 1999; Kinoshita et al.,
2000; Kuhtz-Buschbeck et al., 2001; Middleton & Strick, 2000). In simple motor
tasks involving movements of the hand, all other motor cortices were active in
concert with the primary motor cortex (Kinoshita et al., 2000; Kuhtz-Buschbeck et
al., 2001; Roland et al., 1980). More complex sequential finger movements acti-
vated the supplementary motor area and also these cortical motor areas, which
were active in simple motor tasks of the fingers (Rao et al., 1997). The undifferen-
tiated grip force output generated in at least 3 of 5 ALS patients may have resulted
from the impaired cortical processing of the descending motor commands overrid-
ing the anticipatory grip force planning provided by an intact internal model prob-
ably implemented within the cerebellum.
It is difficult to speculate on the reasons why two ALS patients (A.K. and
G.A.) were able to adequately adjust the grip force profile to the differential load-
ing requirements resulting from upward and downward movements. One possible
explanation is that the functional motor impairment was less severe in these 2
patients, resulting in a similar precise temporal regulation of the grip force profile
as observed in healthy subjects. However, the clinical disability, as assessed by the
ALS severity scale (Hillel et al., 1989), was not significantly different in these 2
patients compared to the other ALS patients (compare Table 1), indicating that
clinical disability measures are not sufficiently correlated with impairments of grip
force regulation. Follow-up investigations are required to study how manipulative
forces are affected by progressive motor deficits during the clinical course of ALS.
Impairments of fine finger movements leading to profound disability in the activi-
ties of daily living are frequent during the natural course of ALS. We observed that
ALS patients produced inefficiently elevated grip forces when holding and mov-
ing a hand-held object. In 3 of 5 patients, the grip and load force profiles were not
adequately processed to match the differential effects of movement direction on
the object loading. The undifferentiated grip force output in ALS should result
from deficient motor execution and/or impaired movement coordination overrid-
ing the precise anticipatory motor planning provided by an intact internal model.
The analysis of grip force in motor neuron disease is sufficient to demonstrate
deficits of automatic manual motor control and offers unique insights into the dis-
tinct processes of movement planning and movement execution.
